"Roy S., Harris R.N., Rao R.U.M., Chapman D.S.","Climate change in India inferred from geothermal observations",2002,"Journal of Geophysical Research B: Solid Earth","107","7",,"5","1",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0037055368&partnerID=40&md5=c893da540fce2b7681004dcfca5f9875","National Geophysical Research Inst., Hyderabad, India; Department of Geology/Geophysics, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT, United States","Roy, S., National Geophysical Research Inst., Hyderabad, India; Harris, R.N., Department of Geology/Geophysics, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT, United States; Rao, R.U.M., National Geophysical Research Inst., Hyderabad, India; Chapman, D.S., Department of Geology/Geophysics, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT, United States","Temporal variations in surface ground temperature impart a signal to the subsurface thermal regime that is captured in borehole temperature-depth profiles. Seventy temperature-depth profiles in India, located between 12° and 28°N, are analyzed to infer past changes in ground temperature. These profiles exhibit predominantly positive anomalous temperatures relative to the background thermal regime beginning at depths of 75 - 150 m and increasing toward the surface. This pattern is consistent with warming over the past century. An interpretation in terms of linear surface temperature change indicates warming of about 0.9° ± 0.1°C over the past 150 years. Relatively complete surface air temperature (SAT) records from meteorological stations near the boreholes indicates similar rates of warming over the last century. A combined analysis of borehole temperatures and SAT records yields a long-term, preobservational mean temperature, 0.8° ±0.1°C lower than the 1961 - 1990 mean SAT. When the most recent decade is included directly in the analysis, the average total warming in India from the early 1800s to the late 1990s is ∼1.2°C.","Borehole temperatures; Climate change; Global warming; India","borehole; climate change; geothermal system; temperature; India",,,,,,"Beck, A.E., Judge, A., Analysis of heat flow data, I, detailed observations in a single borehole (1969) Geophys. J. R. Astron. Soc., 18, pp. 145-158; Beltrami, H., Chapman, D.S., Drilling for a past climate (1994) New Sci., 1922, pp. 36-40; Beltrami, H., Cheng, L., Mareschal, J.C., Simultaneous inversion of borehole temperature data for determination of ground surface temperature history (1997) Geophys. J. Int., 129, pp. 311-318; Blackwell, D.D., Steele, J.L., Brott, C.A., The terrain effect on terrestrial heat flow (1980) J. Geophys. Res., 85, pp. 4757-4772; Carslaw, H.S., Jaeger, J.C., (1959) Conduction of Heat in Solids, , 2nd ed., 386 pp. Oxford Univ. Press, New York; Cermak, V., Bodri, L., Safanda, J., Recent climatic change recorded in the underground: Evidence from Cuba (1992) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol., 98, pp. 219-224; Chapman, D.S., Chisholm, T.J., Harris, R.N., Combining borehole temperature and meteorologic data to constrain past climate change (1992) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol., 98, pp. 269-281; Chisholm, T.J., Chapman, D.S., Climate change inferred from analysis of borehole temperature: An example from western Utah (1992) J. Geophys. Res., 97, pp. 14155-14175; Clauser, C., Mareschall, J.-C., Ground temperature history in central Europe from borehole temperature data (1995) Geophys J. Int., 121, pp. 805-817; Clow, G.D., The extent of temporal smearing in surface-temperature histories derived from borehole temperature measurements (1992) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol., 98, pp. 81-86; Crowley, T.J., Lowery, T.S., How warm was the Medieval warm period? (2000) Ambio, 29, pp. 51-54; Deming, D., Evidence for climatic warming in North America from analysis of borehole temperature (1995) Science, 268, pp. 1576-1577; Ellsaesser, H.W., MacCracken, M.C., Walton, J.J., Grotch, S.L., Global climatic trends as revealed by the recorded data (1986) Rev. Geophys., 24, p